{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486853"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:47:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:47:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"190"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/190"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.14,0.6,0.04,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49547"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/190"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34818"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11522"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12288"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42022"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49547"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department by ambulance following a fall at home. She was found on the floor by her son several hours after the fall, as she was unable to get up. The patient did not sustain any fractures during the fall, however several large bruises are noted on the right buttocks and thigh, with mild pitting oedema to her bilateral ankles. She complains of muscle pain and has passed some dark coloured urine. She has a known history of hypertension, heart failure and hypercholesterolaemia and is compliant with all her medications. Some basic laboratory investigations (Image 1) and an ECG (Image 2) are performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium gluconate","Furosemide","Isotonic saline","Haemodialysis","Concentrated albumin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe immediate concern must be possible rhabdomyolysis. Whilst rhabdomyolysis may not appear for one to three days after muscle injury, the effects can come on much sooner. Hydration therapy with isotonic crystalloid infusion is the first line of treatment for rhabdomyolysis. In this case the patient will only require \u003Cstrong\u003Eisotonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E to be given.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcentrated albumin\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for rhabdomyolysis as initial management. The primary goal is to maintain adequate urine output and prevent renal failure through fluid resuscitation, with isotonic crystalloid solutions as first line.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no strong evidence for \u003Cstrong\u003Efurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E in rhabdomyolysis and it is definitely not first line therapy. Whilst this patient has a history of heart failure, she has only mild pitting oedema with no other features of significant overload. Fluid resuscitation would take priority, with care given to monitor her fluid status throughout. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst hyperkalaemia can occur in rhabdomyolysis, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium gluconate\u003C/strong\u003E would not be given in the absence of a raised potassium level or any ECG changes. In this case her serum potassium is not elevated and there are no ECG changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E is only indicated in patients not responsive to hydration therapy or if anuric.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rhabdomyolysis and hyperkalaemia must always be considered in patients with major bruising and muscle injury."],"references":["Petejova N, Martinek A. Acute kidney injury due to rhabdomyolysis and renal replacement therapy: a critical review. Crit Care. 2014;18(3):224. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4056317/","Sauret JM, Marinides G, Wang GK. Rhabdomyolysis. Am Fam Physician. 2002;65(5):907-12. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2002/0301/p907.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34818"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"190"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17285"},{"type":"media","id":"17286"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17285"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/10fda449-5bc0-42b0-9111-a9a02ee53aea.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/10fda449-5bc0-42b0-9111-a9a02ee53aea.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":329}},{"type":"media","id":"17286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17286"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/42aa0078-ebf8-4132-8118-9f7c3555964e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/42aa0078-ebf8-4132-8118-9f7c3555964e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":426}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34818","link